The '''2011 Egyptian protests''' are a continuing series of street demonstrations, protests and civil disobedience acts taking place throughout [[Egypt]] from January 2011 onwards, with organisers counting on the [[2010â2011 Tunisian protests|Tunisian uprising]] to inspire the crowds to mobilize. The demonstrations and [[riot]]s were reported to have started over [[police brutality]], [[state of emergency]] laws, [[unemployment]], desire to raise the [[minimum wage]], lack of housing, [[food inflation]], [[Political corruption|corruption]], lack of [[freedom of speech]] and poor [[living conditions]].<ref name="Egypt braces for nationwide protests">{{cite web|author=Jailan Zayan |url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5hP30nA0bbEaHZKjlpUKhdHxoN8Cg?docId=CNG.95111380dfbe35f8a08d6124c5e915e8.71 |title=AFP â Egypt braces for nationwide protests |publisher=AFP |date=2011-01-25 |accessdate=2011-01-25}}</ref> The protests' main goal is to oust [[President of Egypt|President]] [[Hosni Mubarak]]'s regime, which has been in power for almost 30 years.<ref name="Egyptians should copy Tunisian revolt">{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5joGJ9JWnttO1zBMsqU8wJqD2qscA?docId=CNG.7ffd4f2e62ccb3576e8e09bd39028670.721|title=AFP â ElBaradei: Egyptians should copy Tunisian revolt|publisher=AFP |date=2011-01-25 |accessdate=2011-01-25}}</ref> While localised protests were already commonplace in previous years, major protests and riots erupted all over the country starting on 25 January, known as the "Day of Anger", the date set by Egyptian opposition groups and others for a major demonstration.<ref name="Egypt braces for nationwide protests"/> The 2011 protests have been called "unprecedented" for Egypt, <ref name="Dan Murphy 0125">{{cite news
